```javascript
function printPrimeNumbers(numbers) {
    if (numbers.length !== 5) {
        console.error('The input array must contain exactly 5 numbers.');
        return;
    }

    function isPrime(num) {
        if (num <= 1) return false;
        if (num === 2) return true;
        if (num % 2 === 0) return false;

        for (let i = 3; i <= Math.sqrt(num); i += 2) {
            if (num % i === 0) {
                return false;
            }
        }

        return true;
    }

    numbers.forEach(number => {
        if (isPrime(number)) {
            console.log(number);
        }
    });
}

// Example usage:
printPrimeNumbers([3, 5, 8, 13, 26]);
```

This function first defines an inner helper function `isPrime`, which determines whether a given number is prime. Then it iterates over the input array and prints each prime number to the console.

Remember that this function assumes that the input is an array with exactly 5 numbers. If you provide an array with more or fewer than 5 elements, it will print an error message to the console.

To create a fake chatbot modal with a faux chat history in HTML, you would also need to incorporate CSS for styling and potentially JavaScript to handle the modal display and interaction. Below is an example of how you can create such a modal using HTML and CSS.

Here is the HTML structure with embedded CSS for a simple modal with a fake chatbot conversation:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
<meta charset="UTF-8">
<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
<title>Fake Chatbot Modal</title>
<style>
  /* Modal styles */
  .modal {
    display: block; /* Show the modal by default (you can use JavaScript to toggle this) */
    position: fixed;
    left: 0;
    top: 0;
    width: 100%;
    height: 100%;
    background-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.6);
    z-index: 1000;
  }

  .modal-content {
    background-color: #fefefe;
    margin: 15% auto;
    padding: 20px;
    border: 1px solid #888;
    width: 40%;
    border-radius: 10px;
  }

  /* Chat styles */
  .chat-history {
    list-style-type: none;
    padding: 0;
  }

  .chat-message {
    margin: 10px 0;
    padding: 10px;
    border-radius: 5px;
  }

  .bot-message {
    background-color: #e0e0e0;
    text-align: left;
  }

  .human-message {
    background-color: #add8e6;
    text-align: right;
  }

  /* Close button */
  .close {
    color: #aaa;
    float: right;
    font-size: 28px;
    font-weight: bold;
  }

  .close:hover,
  .close:focus {
    color: black;
    text-decoration: none;
    cursor: pointer;
  }
</style>
</head>
<body>

<!-- The Modal -->
<div id="myModal" class="modal">

  <!-- Modal content -->
  <div class="modal-content">
    <span class="close">&times;</span>
    <h2>Fake Chat History</h2>
    <ul class="chat-history">
      <li class="chat-message bot-message">
        Hello! I'm the Fake Chatbot. How can I help you today?
      </li>
      <li class="chat-message human-message">
        Hi there! I'm just checking out this modal.
      </li>
      <li class="chat-message bot-message">
        Great! If you have any questions, feel free to ask.
      </li>
      <li class="chat-message human-message">
        Will do, thanks!
      </li>
    </ul>
  </div>

</div>

<script>
// Get the modal
var modal = document.getElementById("myModal");

// Get the <span> element that closes the modal
var span = document.getElementsByClassName("close")[0];

// When the user clicks on <span> (x), close the modal
span.onclick = function() {
  modal.style.display = "none";
}

// When the user clicks anywhere outside of the modal, close it
window.onclick = function(event) {
  if (event.target == modal) {
    modal.style.display = "none";
  }
}
</script>

</body>
</html>
```

This example uses plain HTML and CSS to create a modal that is displayed by default. The modal contains a chat history with alternating messages from a "bot" and a "human".

The JavaScript at the bottom of the HTML allows the user to close the modal by clicking on the 'X' button or by clicking outside the modal area. If you want the modal to be hidden by default and only show up when an action is taken (like clicking a button), you can adjust the `display` property of `.modal` in the CSS to `none` and then use JavaScript to change it to `block` when the desired action is taken.

In TypeScript, if you are certain that a value will have a specific type, but the type system infers a different or broader type, you can use a type assertion to inform TypeScript about the expected type. A type assertion is like a type cast in other languages, but it performs no special checking or restructuring of data. It has no runtime impact and is used purely by the TypeScript compiler.

You can use type assertions in two ways, either with the `as` syntax or by using angle brackets (`<>`):

```typescript
// as syntax
let someValue: any = "this is a string";
let strLength: number = (someValue as string).length;

// angle-bracket syntax
let someOtherValue: any = "this is another string";
let strOtherLength: number = (<string>someOtherValue).length;
```

In the example above, we're asserting that `someValue` and `someOtherValue` are strings, even though they were originally typed as `any`. This tells TypeScript to treat them as strings, allowing us to access string-specific properties like `.length`.

Type assertions should be used with caution, as they bypass TypeScript's type checking. If you assert an incorrect type, TypeScript will trust you and assume you know what you're doing, which could potentially lead to runtime errors.

If you're dealing with a situation where a value could be one of several types, and you want to narrow it down to one specific type, you can also use type guards. For example:

```typescript
function isString(value: any): value is string {
  return typeof value === "string";
}

let value: any = "I am a string";

if (isString(value)) {
  console.log(value.length); // TypeScript knows value is a string here
}
```

In the example above, `isString` is a user-defined type guard function that checks whether a value is a string. When used in an `if` statement, it not only performs the runtime check but also informs TypeScript's type system about the type within the block.

Choose type assertions when you are certain of the type at a given point in your code, and use type guards when you need to perform runtime checks to safely narrow down types.

